args: This is the exercise field where we train\nour test subjects for combat.
(The more I look at Researcher 241,\nthe more he resembles my husband.)
(But it can't be him. Because he's...)
Stay with me, my love!\nI can save you!
You of all people should know this man\nis beyond saving.
Were the escaped subjects Tf-997\nand Tf-999 behind this?
We're going to investigate. Take the body\nto the lab. Once the autopsy is complete,\nreturn it to Researcher 90.
You're going to let her bury him, sir?
Permitting her to observe the basic rituals\nof death will give her the strength to carry\non with her research.
(I know for a fact my husband is dead\nbecause I buried him with my own hands.)
*gasp* *wheeze* I...I can't do it...\nMy body won't move anymore...
After all the enhancements we gave you,\nyou can't do something this simple?
Well, sounds like this one's a dud.\nAnd you know what that means...
(They're going to dispose of that man.\nI must do something!)
(But how do I do so without revealing that\nI am betraying the Syndicate?)
One moment, solider. I think perhaps\nyou're being a bit too hasty on this.
Number 241, was it? You're aware that we\nare supposed to dispose of subjects who\nfail to meet our standards, yes?

I am. However, the time required for our
modifications to take effect varies from
subject to subject. It's possible you are
simply being impatient with this man.
I can't afford to waste space holding on \nto people for who knows how long,\nhoping that we finally see results.
The Preceptor said we should focus on\nraising our success rate, did he not?
Please, give this man time. I will step up\nand assume all blame for asking you to\nstay your judgment.
Well, if you're taking the fall, then sure.
Just do your best during this training,\nyoung man. No complaints. Understood?
No! I don't understand!\nI don't understand ANYTHING!
You kidnapped me, experimented on me,\nand forced me into this insane training\nregimen! Why?! Why me?!
I understand how confused you must be,\nbut you mustn't lose heart.
Every storm has an end, and every night\na dawn. If you can but weather this,\nI know there are sunny days ahead.
This is the reference room where we store\nresults of the procedures, records of test\nsubjects, and the like.
Er, and I suppose that concludes the tour.\nDo you have any questions?
You seem to care about your test subjects.\nWhy?
The Syndicate would likely not be too\nhappy with me about this...
But I don't believe any life is disposable.
You are quite kind. It is one more\nquality you both have in common.
Sorry, who do I share that quality with?
My husband was also a researcher.\nSadly, I...I lost him a short while ago.
You resemble him to a shocking degree.\nYour looks, your speech—even the way\nyou move about.
He even used to say the line you just did:\n＂Every storm has an end, and every night\na dawn.＂
So when I look at you, I can't help but\nwonder if he somehow...came back to life.
...I have one more place I'd like to show\nyou, Number 90. Come with me.
You can see the entire lake from here...\nIt's really quite beautiful.
There's a fissure in the depths of the\ncavern that leads here.

Sometimes when I'm stuck on something
in my research, I'll come here to get a
breath of fresh air. I suppose it's my own
secret hideaway, in a sense.
And why did you bring me here?
Because I brought up some hard memories\nfor you—about your husband, I mean.
Is this supposed to cheer me?
A sad attempt, I know, but I fear research\nis the only thing I have any real talent for.
You're even as awkward as he was...
I know your husband and I were both\nresearchers for the Syndicate, but...\nI'm not him. I'm sorry.
Still, it's clear that your husband lives on\nin your heart.
So please let go of that pain if you can.\nI'm sure your husband would not have\nwanted that for you, after all.
I live on, carrying the burden of his hopes.
Thank you, Barth. Oh, and I am Grace.
(Barth is right. Even though they share so\nmany qualities, he is not my husband.)
(But then why does my heart beat so fast\nwhen I am around him...?)
